IMO it's confusing to have both run() and main() with slightly different semantics.  Do we expect there to be a lot of custom TensorBoards out there that are already calling `main.main` from their own code (like `main.create_tb_app` and the other deprecated ones below)?

I'd favor moving towards having just a single `main()` function here that basically does

```python
def main():
  def bound_main(unused_argv=None):
    return program.main(default.get_plugins(), default.get_assets_zip_provider())
  tf.app.run(bound_main)
```

Then basically users can choose to either use TensorBoard's existing `main()` function here exactly as-is, or copy it and tweak as needed, e.g. if they wanted to execute their own `tf.app.run()` for some reason.

Right now there are three separate entry points that users could choose from - `program.main()` just does the core work, `main.main()` adds in the default plugins and assets, and `main.run()` adds in `tf.app.run()` (in reality there's even an earlier level where users don't even use the premade `program.main()`, like internally).  That seems a bit more complicated than we really need - I think we should aim for just a "do everything" one (here) and a "lets you customize plugins and assets" one (`program.main`).

@mrocklin, I'd be curious to hear your thoughts on how we can better handle unknown chunks/divisions here. The stuff here and further down (directly assigning `._chunks`) is pretty hacky.

In this case, since we're going `da.Array` with unknown chunks -> `dd.DataFrame`, we known we'll end up with a RangeIndex, so as long as we know the length of each chunk we can compute the divsions.

I *think* that having `dd.from_dask_array` took an optional `divisions` argument (or maybe `chunks`?) would be the cleanest way to support this. We could actually require that the argument be provided when there are any unknown divisions, since currently you end up with incorrect results when the dask array as unknown chunks.

